    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey can u explain what the principle of least privilege actually means in a business network? like how would a company actually use it in real life?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Principle of Least Privilege (PoLP) is the rule that a user or system should only have the minimum level of access necessary to perform their specific job, and nothing more. In a business network, this is often visualized as a castle with a single, narrow gate that only the specific guard (the user) can open, rather than a giant door that anyone can walk through.\n\nImagine a company's network as a sprawling, magical forest where every employee is a tiny, mischievous goblin. If a goblin is given a key to the entire forest, they can easily steal the treasure, break the trees, or even turn the sun into a goblin. That is the danger of giving too much access.\n\nIn real life, a company would set up a \"goblin\" named Alice who needs to manage the payroll. Alice would be given a key only to the payroll vault, not the entire castle. If Alice tries to open the door to the CEO's office, the goblin will be stuck, and the door will remain locked. This prevents a single goblin from accidentally causing a massive disaster.\n\nIf a goblin needs to move a heavy box, they might need a small, sturdy key.",
